WEBVTT

00:00.352 --> 00:05.274
Hello everyone, welcome back to another episode of the Grand Prixquel podcast where we discuss all things feeder series.

00:05.594 --> 00:14.278
On today's episode, we are going to be doing a review of the Eurocup 3 and F2 races that have just happened this weekend.

00:15.579 --> 00:20.041
Your hosts today are myself, Robin, Peter, Hayden, Evan, and Keenan.

00:25.089 --> 00:27.251
So do we want to start with Eurocup 3?

00:28.773 --> 00:30.254
There's a lot- there's a lot to say.

00:30.935 --> 00:40.884
I think firstly, we need to mention we've had of course Linus Lundqvist announced to race in EC3, which if you don't know who he is, he's a former IndyCar driver.

00:42.525 --> 00:59.438
He raced with Chip Ganassi Racing and in 2024 he took two podiums and he won a lot of series back in America, Indy Lights, Formula Regional Americas and also British F3, which he won with the same team he's now with in EC3, I mean.

01:00.238 --> 01:04.702
I think this just shows IndyCar is a feeder series to Eurocup 3.

01:05.622 --> 01:06.183
Exactly.

01:07.166 --> 01:09.268
Just get all the IndyCar drivers here.

01:09.649 --> 01:12.292
Alex Palou should race for Palou Motorsport.

01:13.033 --> 01:21.102
I mean, he owns them and given how Palou Motorsport did this weekend, maybe James Egozi is secretly Alex Palou or something like.

01:21.668 --> 01:29.731
To add on to that, actually, because I know everyone came into the season thinking, you know, it's gonna be another season of MP-Campos dominance.

01:30.051 --> 01:32.832
But like, clearly that was not the case.

01:32.952 --> 01:37.693
I mean, we saw Palou up there with Egozi getting three podiums in three races.

01:38.013 --> 01:42.535
And we saw Hitech up there with Al Azhari getting pole and also a win.

01:43.375 --> 01:50.777
I mean, apparently this is the first weekend in EC3 history where there's been no race won by MP or Campos.

01:50.837 --> 01:56.498
Well, I'm very bad at remembering which drivers are on which teams.

01:57.098 --> 02:02.820
I know Powell is on Campos, but who are Powell's teammates?

02:03.200 --> 02:11.967
Yeah, so Powell's teammates at Campos have not had a very good weekend and it's kind of like- I've been underwhelmed massively by Campos as a whole.

02:12.247 --> 02:14.369
I mean Powell was the only one who had a good weekend.

02:14.409 --> 02:31.002
I mean Strauven was just massively struggling the entire time, and like everyone obviously rates Strauven looking at his Spanish F4 championship, and I also thought he would be doing really well but this weekend he has not been up there and,

02:32.703 --> 02:35.264
same with like, Heuzenroeder, for example.

02:35.584 --> 02:44.588
He had issues during qualifying that put him in P30 for races one and two, race two being the sprint race.

02:45.529 --> 02:54.453
And he did eventually get a decent position compared to the P30 in qualifying two.

02:54.493 --> 02:58.214
I think he started race three in P15.

02:59.295 --> 03:01.696
And he did make some really

03:02.297 --> 03:04.440
Good overtakes throughout the weekend.

03:05.001 --> 03:11.872
Like I think in his Instagram post he said he had like 24 overtakes over the weekend, which is kind of crazy.

03:12.280 --> 03:14.442
It really all is down to qualifying.

03:14.462 --> 03:20.646
I think next time out he just needs to get that, but still, I mean, it wasn't entirely-

03:20.666 --> 03:23.469
You’d expect more from a Spanish F4 champion.

03:24.029 --> 03:28.032
Yeah, and the GB3 runner-up from last season.

03:28.893 --> 03:31.955
And Tarnvanichkul was kind of, he was a bit...

03:32.415 --> 03:33.556
He was there, I guess.

03:34.117 --> 03:35.738
Nothing overly impressive.

03:37.759 --> 03:42.423
He was on the podium for the sprint, but that's because the sprint was a reverse grid race.

03:43.128 --> 03:54.611
Yeah, I think this leads us nicely into talking about race one itself, so of course we had, with James Egozi winning, Rene Lammers in second, and a certain Alex Powell in third.

03:54.951 --> 04:01.252
I mean, the top five, there was very much no surprise, because we had Ean Eyckmans coming in second and Gianmarco Pradel coming in fifth.

04:01.672 --> 04:05.173
So these are very much the five drivers we'd expect to be up there.

04:05.893 --> 04:12.895
But surprisingly, the polesitter Al Azhari stalled off the start, but he recovered really well from that.

04:13.255 --> 04:13.455
Yeah.

04:13.876 --> 04:15.317
That scared me so bad.

04:15.877 --> 04:33.872
Every single time, well especially considering he was at the very front of the field, every single time a car stalls like in the, anywhere really, but any kind of car stalls, but especially in the front like that, I always get flashbacks.

04:34.252 --> 04:36.954
To like last year, Italian F4,

04:37.815 --> 04:39.516
Oh my god, the Imola crash, yeah.

04:39.576 --> 04:40.056
Imola.

04:40.436 --> 04:48.461
I literally, so I, I stopped breathing for a second, but thankfully no one made contact with Al Azhari, but...

04:48.601 --> 04:50.902
Yeah, a great job from all the drivers.

04:51.322 --> 04:55.684
Did a great job avoiding him, and then he, I think he dropped back to around P27, P28.

04:55.704 --> 04:59.466
Not entirely sure, because the timing tower only shows the top 25.

04:59.546 --> 05:06.010
He was out of that top 25, and then he recovered all the way to P7, recovery drive and,

05:07.265 --> 05:16.329
It really leaves questions, if he didn’t stall, where could he have- I think he’d have probably easily won, as we saw in race 3, he had a hand over Egozi.

05:16.329 --> 05:22.791
I think he could’ve won for sure. I think it would have been a fight with him, I think it would have been a fight with him and Egozi.

05:23.328 --> 05:24.949
Yeah, similar to race three.

05:25.149 --> 05:25.430
Yeah.

05:26.090 --> 05:34.057
Egozi was, I mean, Egozi kind of like, you know, he took the lead and he, like, he controlled the race once he took the lead, got him.

05:34.757 --> 05:38.580
And I guess, you know, maybe he heard my comments on the preview ep.

05:39.321 --> 05:40.422
He took it personally.

05:40.462 --> 05:42.523
He’s not a winter series merchant, I guess.

05:44.185 --> 05:45.106
I love Egozi.

05:45.286 --> 05:47.928
I love his race craft.

05:48.028 --> 05:50.550
He was so fun to watch in all three races.

05:51.563 --> 05:56.731
The fights at the front in the races were really good, like race 1 and race 3 especially.

05:57.291 --> 06:05.664
The fight between Egozi, Lammers and Powell scared the hell out of me because I was on the edge of my seat being scared that Alex would crash.

06:06.705 --> 06:18.911
Because for whatever reason, he just cannot behave himself around Rene Lammers, and this is more of a race three thing, because he got penalized in race three for, um, for overtaking Lammers off track.

06:19.551 --> 06:26.135
And I remember the infamous Jarama penalty was because he overtook Lammers before the safety car line.

06:26.855 --> 06:29.336
Can he behave himself around Rene Lammers, please?

06:29.356 --> 06:33.098
This is like Victor Martins and Alex Dunne, like,

06:34.878 --> 06:37.219
Yeah, but, I mean, Lammers also had a good weekend.

06:37.279 --> 06:43.423
I mean, he was unfortunate to lose the lead in race one, but, you know, P2 is still really good, especially, you know, rookie win.

06:43.443 --> 06:47.065
I would say I was a bit underwhelmed by Linus Lundqvist.

06:47.465 --> 06:49.726
As I mentioned before, I was expecting quite a bit.

06:50.267 --> 06:55.510
Okay, maybe he's not in the best team, but, I mean, his performance was similar to teammate Bart Harrison.

06:56.470 --> 06:58.471
Yeah, he's not entirely down to the team.

06:58.811 --> 07:02.614
And it's not like... it's not like... Bart Harrison is, um...

07:03.654 --> 07:05.495
a bright talent or anything.

07:05.835 --> 07:16.358
And we know how, I mean, maybe this is all a bit last minute, maybe we'll see more in the upcoming rounds, if he is even doing more upcoming rounds, cause… wasn't he just doing the first round?

07:16.798 --> 07:20.379
It's not entirely been announced, so we don't really know.

07:20.399 --> 07:23.300
I would like to see him cook, but I also don’t want to...

07:23.560 --> 07:25.040
His reputation to get ruined.

07:25.540 --> 07:26.741
Going back to Powell...

07:27.081 --> 07:28.621
Going back to Powell, um...

07:28.941 --> 07:30.022
It's always Alex Powell.

07:30.422 --> 07:31.462
Sanson mentioned,

07:31.922 --> 07:42.370
how he thinks that he's confident that Powell will be picked up by an Academy and I'm praying, because we know that, I think it was Audi that was there for sure or- no, that was at FREC.

07:42.810 --> 07:55.179
I think um, but Audi has been scouting in general and so has Cadillac, I still I'm hoping I'm praying I'm praying that Alex gets picked up

07:55.939 --> 07:58.321
by either Audi or Cadillac.

07:58.902 --> 08:13.835
Haas doesn't have a junior team really, other than Kaylee Countryman in F1 Academy, but I don't think she really is technically part of the Academy. But they need to make the Academy, the Haas junior team, just for Alex Powell.

08:14.456 --> 08:15.697
You know, America, woo!

08:16.722 --> 08:18.643
Yeah, get the American on there.

08:19.523 --> 08:22.424
Or they should, they should, they should put Egozi on there too.

08:22.624 --> 08:25.965
They should just have an all-American lineup.

08:26.305 --> 08:27.145
Just Floridians.

08:27.446 --> 08:28.186
Just the Floridians.

08:28.226 --> 08:32.467
You have Sebastian Wheldon and James Egozi and Alex Powell.

08:32.847 --> 08:34.168
What other Floridians are there?

08:34.188 --> 08:36.208
You know, get Logan Sargeant in there somehow. 

08:36.288 --> 08:36.629
I don't know.

08:36.929 --> 08:37.569
Figure it out.

08:38.169 --> 08:41.314
I think Race 2 was just as enjoyable as Race 1.

08:41.354 --> 08:44.418
I mean, it was really nice to see El Feghali winning.

08:44.558 --> 08:52.169
I mean, this was the first time we actually heard the Lebanese anthem played on the top step of an FIA accredited podium.

08:52.630 --> 08:54.272
I got really emotional, actually.

08:55.133 --> 08:58.094
It's always nice to see these smaller nations doing well.

08:58.114 --> 09:03.737
Because often, you know, motorsports is very much dominated by, you know, European countries.

09:04.517 --> 09:05.998
But it was nice to see that.

09:06.018 --> 09:10.080
I mean, I always love to see smaller countries doing well.

09:10.100 --> 09:15.082
And, you know, of course, you know, reverse grid race, but he still controlled it entirely.

09:16.002 --> 09:19.203
I love his racecraft as well, even when he's in the middle of the field.

09:19.743 --> 09:25.025
I love watching him race, because I think he has amazing racecraft.

09:25.165 --> 09:27.125
So to see him at the front too, especially.

09:27.145 --> 09:32.627
It was very fun to watch, and the win was more than deserved.

09:33.387 --> 09:43.370
I mean, we also saw Thomas Strauven getting some points, which is nice to see, because he's obviously struggled quite a bit this weekend.

09:43.986 --> 09:45.268
Is it a thing with Campos?

09:45.328 --> 09:50.433
I feel like Campos just... maybe Alex Powell cursed them somehow.

09:51.234 --> 09:52.656
I don't know what's going on over there.

09:52.676 --> 09:54.658
He brought his luck.

09:55.178 --> 09:57.741
He gave his bad luck to the entire rest of the team.

09:57.942 --> 09:58.322
Yeah.

09:58.562 --> 10:01.505
He gave his bad luck.

10:01.646 --> 10:02.647
He got lucky-ish.

10:05.056 --> 10:14.064
He did well, even with the penalties, but I guess he got lucky-ish, so his bad luck just got transferred to the rest of the team.

10:14.084 --> 10:15.306
It rubbed off on the rest of them.

10:16.166 --> 10:23.373
Another thing about race 2, Eyckmans just spinning out after the checkered flag.

10:24.414 --> 10:26.136
I don't even know what happened.

10:26.677 --> 10:35.568
I mean, for him, still finished in P4, despite, like, you know, the spinning out at the end, which is kind of the funniest thing ever.

10:36.149 --> 10:38.992
I mean, it's a perfect time to do it, if you think about it, because-

10:39.713 --> 10:41.734
I mean, you don't lose anything.

10:42.094 --> 10:44.055
You could just pretend they're doughnuts.

10:45.095 --> 10:48.936
I mean, maybe he just didn't want to do the cool down lap.

10:49.016 --> 10:51.157
He just thought, missed out on the podium.

10:51.177 --> 10:52.838
He was like, you know what, I've had enough.

10:53.198 --> 10:54.338
I'm just going to leave it here.

10:54.358 --> 10:55.819
Maybe that was his thinking.

10:56.459 --> 10:58.600
And I mean, Egozi again, great.

10:58.640 --> 11:04.602
I mean, he started, you know, towards the lower half of the top 10 because of the reverse grid.

11:04.622 --> 11:05.843
And he still recovered to P3, I mean.

11:06.643 --> 11:09.752
He climbed up, he climbed positions pretty quickly.

11:10.346 --> 11:18.373
Powell had a bit of a bad start, but then he started in P9, because he qualified P4, was it?

11:18.753 --> 11:25.258
For the first race, so he started in P9, and then he had a bad start, and then went back up to P9 at the end.

11:26.019 --> 11:31.143
Also, Al Azhari made good positions, but not as many as Egozi.

11:31.163 --> 11:38.909
For all of the front contenders, the main thing in these sprint races really comes down to how many positions can you make up?

11:39.750 --> 11:47.916
And I mean, Egozi is certainly the one doing their best at the moment, but we saw in Race 1 how good Al Azhari could be at making up positions as well.

11:47.936 --> 12:03.707
I also want to point out in both race 1 and race 2, the other Hitechs were fighting with each other, nearly crashing into each other, which was quite funny and... And as Jake Sanson says, rule number one of motorsport is that you don't crash into your teammate.

12:04.067 --> 12:05.408
Don't tell Alex Dunne that.

12:05.428 --> 12:08.511
I think someone needs to remind Alex Dunne after Australia.

12:09.665 --> 12:15.087
And the Premas in Australia, both of those ignored that advice.

12:15.847 --> 12:27.412
But luckily for Al Azhari, I mean, in race 1, even Al Azhari nearly got tangled in it, but I think, you know, he's very much kind of their main guy, so maybe they were like, oh crap, we can't go into him.

12:28.112 --> 12:34.595
This fight between Egozi and Al Azhari, I feel like lead us into race 3, because race 3 was peak.

12:35.355 --> 12:40.819
That was the most entertaining, like, oh my gosh.

12:41.199 --> 12:43.360
Watching them at the front, that was just so good.

12:43.660 --> 12:45.381
I was, like, on the edge of my seat.

12:45.782 --> 12:48.343
Like, it was the whole time, too.

12:48.403 --> 12:50.905
It wasn't just like, it was the whole race.

12:51.125 --> 12:53.807
And oh, that was so, that was incredible.

12:54.512 --> 12:59.674
Dude, I was waiting for them to crash into each other so that Powell gets the win, but then he got penalised anyways.

13:00.094 --> 13:05.816
I feel really bad for Pradel, because he was P2, and then he just broke down under the safety car.

13:06.096 --> 13:13.639
He started on pole, lost that on the lead, but he was still a P2, and then under safety car, his car just was like, I've had enough.

13:14.239 --> 13:18.881
And he'd had, and he’d been having a solid weekend, he'd taken P5 in the earlier two races.

13:19.281 --> 13:23.763
So like, he was having a solid weekend, and for it to end like that is just a bit unfortunate, because

13:24.223 --> 13:25.883
It was a really good weekend otherwise.

13:26.543 --> 13:30.064
But then again, it gave us that amazing, Egozi-Al Azhari fight.

13:30.444 --> 13:36.305
I will say, I mean, with Al Azhari first overtake, questionable track limits, it felt like.

13:37.025 --> 13:38.286
He's kind of being off the track.

13:38.506 --> 13:40.106
Can I complain about that, actually?

13:40.126 --> 13:46.067
Because Alex Powell got a penalty for overtaking off track, but then Al Azhari doesn't.

13:46.387 --> 13:50.628
And I'm kind of mad about that because I didn't even see where Alex overtook off track.

13:51.048 --> 13:52.932
Like, when did that happen?

13:53.253 --> 13:55.136
And why did Al Azhari also not get a penalty for it?

13:55.596 --> 14:03.082
The stewards hate the Floridians cause giving Al Azhari a penalty when Egozi wins, aka the Floridian.

14:03.126 --> 14:06.188
This is like the anti-Flordian championship or something.

14:06.809 --> 14:11.192
It is quite funny how initially his penalty was 10 seconds, then it got changed to 5 seconds.

14:11.472 --> 14:13.834
Yeah, they were like, okay, maybe we won't.

14:14.274 --> 14:23.121
And I think, you know, so far we've got kind of five key contenders, basically, which are kind of reflected in the top five of the championship.

14:23.381 --> 14:28.165
Which if you can't tell, Egozi, Al Azhari, Eyckmans, Lammers and Powell.

14:28.621 --> 14:39.284
The thing is with Powell is that he already, before race 3, he got a penalty, a 5 place grid penalty, for not slowing under yellow flags in qualifying.

14:39.584 --> 14:50.588
So when he was supposed to start P3 and could have possibly been in the fight for the lead in the race, he started P8, he fought his way up to P3, got a penalty for overtaking off track and then ended up P5.

14:51.468 --> 14:52.929
He just needs to behave himself.

14:53.430 --> 14:57.193
Like I said earlier, behave yourself around Rene Lammers, please.

14:57.833 --> 15:06.981
I feel like between the fighting at the front and Alex, like, kind of cooking, um, that's just, yeah, this race is just so fun.

15:07.081 --> 15:10.004
Like, Alex, like, the fact, okay.

15:11.898 --> 15:16.906
I just, he always, he gives us like, he gets so close, so many times.

15:17.406 --> 15:20.511
He gets so close, and then something happens.

15:20.531 --> 15:27.561
He got the penalty, he got the flag, or the, um, the penalty for not slowing under the yellows or whatever.

15:28.262 --> 15:40.165
I feel like, every time he gets close to a win or a podium or just fighting for the lead in general, it's like he could never have it because there's always something.

15:40.185 --> 15:47.786
Yeah, like if he hadn't got that penalty, he would be P3 in the championship ahead of Eyckmans and Lammers.

15:48.326 --> 15:51.027
But because of the penalty, he is now P5 in the championship.

15:51.578 --> 16:03.640
I mean, to be fair though, it is really close between those three, I mean, Eyckmans on 34 points, Lammers on 30, Powell on 27 is very, things are very much going to change.

16:04.042 --> 16:06.943
I think we have a really close fight for the rookie championship.

16:07.804 --> 16:08.344
Oh, easily.

16:08.504 --> 16:16.567
And I think even at the front cause, I mean, if I'm honest, Egozi does have a decent lead of 13 points after the first round.

16:17.328 --> 16:21.189
But I mean, that's not entirely, you know, it's not like he's clear out front.

16:21.349 --> 16:25.131
And we've seen, kind of a clear top five across all three races.

16:25.271 --> 16:29.033
And I expect the three rookies to get better and better.

16:29.053 --> 16:31.594
They actually get more experience in these cars.

16:32.174 --> 16:34.136
Well, and will Campos lock in?

16:34.436 --> 16:40.300
Like, they were really bad this round, but will they lock in and at least improve a little bit?

16:40.541 --> 16:42.762
Yeah, they’re P4 in the team's standings.

16:43.022 --> 16:44.123
Which, what the hell?

16:44.684 --> 16:45.885
What are you doing, Campos?

16:46.665 --> 16:48.907
Like, I don't know, can you lock in, please?

16:50.528 --> 16:53.490
This is because we all predicted them for team's champions.

16:53.891 --> 16:55.372
We need to stop doing that.

16:55.993 --> 16:57.875
We have an incredible jinx.

16:58.256 --> 17:00.318
It's, it's... Oh my god.

17:00.678 --> 17:02.440
Our jinxing powers are like crazy.

17:02.460 --> 17:05.704
We need to start reverse psychology.

17:05.824 --> 17:08.007
Reverse psychology, our predictions.

17:08.627 --> 17:12.432
We said Egozi and Al Azhari wouldn’t really replicate their performances.

17:12.532 --> 17:13.813
And now look who's P1 and P2.

17:15.072 --> 17:16.313
Egozi and Al Azhari.

17:16.754 --> 17:20.958
I mean, Palou Motorsport is in P2, I'd say that it’s Alex Palou's fault.

17:21.578 --> 17:25.302
He just can't stop winning wherever he is, or whatever he's involved in.

17:25.322 --> 17:29.907
He's had enough of dominating in IndyCar, he's just come to EC3 for him to dominate that.

17:30.995 --> 17:33.376
And then Hitech are 6 points ahead of Campos.

17:34.076 --> 17:37.557
Um, cause Campos is mostly carried by Powell.

17:38.097 --> 17:42.878
Hitech and Palou are very much being carried by Hitech and Al Azhari though as well.

17:43.518 --> 17:46.759
And then MPs MP, they have Lammers and Eyckmans, so.

17:47.499 --> 17:50.660
Yeah, but I mean, I think this sets up a really exciting championship.

17:51.200 --> 17:58.001
The next round is going to be about a month's time and Portimao, on the 5th to 7th of June with no sprint race this round.

17:58.041 --> 18:00.662
It’s  just going to be the two rac- two feature races.

18:01.262 --> 18:11.847
I'm really sad that we have to wait a month for, because this racing is so good and we have to wait a month until next round and then there's another month until the round after I'm pretty sure.

18:11.867 --> 18:21.951
I mean, as I said earlier, I expect the rookies to just get better and better, so I'm expecting more of Eyckmans, Lammers and Powell fighting for podiums and wins.

18:22.512 --> 18:24.753
And I really hope to see Strauven up there, but...

18:25.873 --> 18:27.053
Let's see how well it goes.

18:27.554 --> 18:28.714
I'm sorry if I jinxed them.

18:29.774 --> 18:39.758
What I notice about this series that I really like is that I feel like in this series more than in some other series is that the rookies perform really well.

18:39.878 --> 18:47.660
They tend to perform really well as compared to some other series where the rookies are usually towards like, except for like maybe a select few.

18:49.061 --> 18:54.703
But I feel like in this series, and maybe it's just because we have really good rookies this year,

18:55.343 --> 19:01.339
like they're fighting for like wins and for championships.

19:02.441 --> 19:09.025
I think a part of it is that, for example, in FREC, anyone who did the winter series is not considered a rookie.

19:09.245 --> 19:17.810
So technically, if you think about it, everyone who's fighting at the front of the field in FREC should be considered rookies other than, you know, like the obvious Ninovic and Al-Dhaheri.

19:18.190 --> 19:29.016
But then here, anyone who competed in the winter series is still a rookie because the regulations say that you must have competed in less than nine, like,

19:29.816 --> 19:34.180
races on the same level as Eurocup 3 before January 1st, 2026.

19:34.200 --> 19:34.420
Oh, okay.

19:37.713 --> 19:46.017
Yeah, like Eyckmans, for example, did eight FREC Races last year, but because he didn't do nine or more, he’s still considered a rookie.

19:46.797 --> 19:47.858
And it's like same with Powell.

19:47.878 --> 19:57.082
Powell did Formula Regional Middle East and the Eurocup 3 Winter series, and yet he's still a rookie because he didn't do those before January 1st.

19:57.582 --> 20:01.804
So I guess it just comes down to who's considered a rookie and who's not.

20:01.844 --> 20:04.566
Like, it depends on each series' regulations.

20:06.247 --> 20:12.395
In terms of predictions, I'm not going to say anything about Alex Powell because I do not want to jinx him.

20:14.237 --> 20:21.987
I think the fight between Egozi and Al Azhari should continue on because I mean you saw them in race 3 that was insane.

20:23.233 --> 20:26.795
And I really underestimated them going into the series.

20:28.076 --> 20:37.762
And I think if we get more racing like we did in Race 3, especially because Paul Ricard isn't really known as a circuit where there's a lot of overtakes.

20:38.102 --> 20:44.426
So if we saw this on Paul Ricard, imagine a circuit where you could actually overtake on, like for example, Monza.

20:45.006 --> 20:46.307
Portimao is going to be peak.

20:47.327 --> 20:49.789
And Portimao is a really nice flowing track as well.

20:49.829 --> 20:51.410
I'm so excited.

20:52.617 --> 20:53.958
Yeah, it's gonna be great.

20:54.319 --> 21:00.225
And I can't wait to see more fights, hopefully involving more drivers than just Egozi and Al Azhari.

21:00.585 --> 21:10.275
I think I'd really like to see some more on track fights between the three rookies, like the three leading rookies, though I need Alex Powell to stay away from Rene Lammers.

21:11.113 --> 21:22.216
Yeah, I also think, I also am thinking that the fight is going to be between Egozi and Al Azhari.

21:23.716 --> 21:33.899
I really hope that Powell is in the fight, but we'll see if Campos, we’ll see if Alex and Campos both lock in.

21:35.459 --> 21:38.940
But I do think it'll be the two that are fighting.

21:40.701 --> 21:52.219
I do hope that we get more of El Feghali like fighting for wins throughout the rest of the season because I love watching him win.

21:54.265 --> 22:03.356
Like I said earlier, I got really emotional because it's not very often that you see Arab drivers winning races outside of, like, you know, the Emiratis.

22:03.876 --> 22:11.465
So I got really emotional over that and I'm waiting for the day we get to see an Egyptian driver in single-seaters and winning races.

22:12.466 --> 22:23.991
I think we can nicely move on to, you know, another certain feeder series, which, unfortunately, I mean, I don't enjoy as much as EC3, but, you know, of course it's Formula 2.

22:24.531 --> 22:26.211
Everybody's favourite Feeder series.

22:26.892 --> 22:32.374
I mean, we mentioned a bit of F2 during the Eurocup 3 stuff when we were talking about Alex Dunne.

22:33.652 --> 22:37.234
Yeah, I mean, yeah, Alex Dunne, well, you hear my thoughts in a bit.

22:37.854 --> 22:43.577
But, I mean, it was interesting, because of course we had the Jeddah and Bahrain rounds cancelled.

22:44.498 --> 22:50.861
So it got replaced with Miami and Canada, which we're going to see.

22:51.542 --> 22:54.784
I think qualifying showed how unserious F2 is.

22:55.804 --> 23:18.344
Yeah I mean I knew going into it that it was going to be a crazy weekend because I mean first time ever in the US, first time ever in North America and I mean I was excited but I knew that it was going to be kind of insane but I don't think I was prepared for quite how crazy it was.

23:19.667 --> 23:22.148
I mean, what do you mean, Maini got Pole?

23:22.168 --> 23:32.054
I mean, partly down to, I guess, Stenshorne got Mechachrome’d, he died, and then Qualifying finished a bit early, so I don't think everybody got to do their final lap.

23:32.634 --> 23:33.515
Maini got Pole.

23:33.915 --> 23:41.259
He stalled in the sprint race, and then, I don't know, what even happened to him in the feature race?

23:41.519 --> 23:42.860
He managed to get fifth, actually.

23:43.280 --> 23:43.800
He what?

23:44.361 --> 23:44.941
He was fifth.

23:45.641 --> 23:46.042
Really?

23:46.906 --> 23:48.427
Yeah, in the feature race.

23:48.787 --> 23:52.350
I guess I just did not see him there, I guess.

23:52.410 --> 23:55.092
I mean, the sprint race, both races were quite fun.

23:55.132 --> 24:01.936
I mean, I want to give props to Nikola Tsolov because he missed a lot of practice, Campos just have an issue.

24:02.617 --> 24:07.700
Qualified P10 despite having very limited practice on this brand new circuit for F2.

24:08.421 --> 24:11.023
Qualified in P10 so he gets the reverse grid pole.

24:11.843 --> 24:25.799
And then he just very much, kind of, he had a good battle with Van Hoepen for the lead, but I mean, they were still fighting for a bit, but I really enjoyed his racecraft, I think, and he's very much been the best driver in F2, I think, so far this year.

24:26.140 --> 24:28.583
Yeah, I love watching Tsolov.

24:29.183 --> 24:29.704
at the front.

24:30.745 --> 24:44.838
I think, you know, we like to, we like to complain about F2 a lot, but I do think we get some really, really good battles in both of the races, especially at the end, like the last, like the feature race was peak.

24:45.499 --> 24:50.141
If that's jump time, you feel like the drivers you should be up there aren't always up there.

24:50.261 --> 24:53.863
I mean, Kush Maini on pole, really says everything.

24:54.244 --> 25:05.409
I think, because, I mean, we've seen the last few years especially, you know, you know how good, I mean, I'm never forgetting 2024, you know, you know how good Bearman and Antonelli are, and they're not at the front.

25:06.110 --> 25:09.331
Victor Martins, we know how good it is, and he’s not been at the front.

25:09.491 --> 25:12.373
That's my main issue with F2, you don't always see these drivers.

25:12.393 --> 25:14.074
I mean, we’ve seen them with, you know,

25:14.814 --> 25:30.004
Colton Herta is almost kind of struggling. I mean it is kind of expected I think because you know Indycar is so different at least, the type of car is so different different tires as well he needs to get used to it, but he's still a multiple Indycar winner

25:30.632 --> 25:39.680
I think new car, new track, new everything for Colton has really, I guess, hurt his chances, I’d say, to do anything pretty good.

25:39.700 --> 25:49.869
I mean, he did manage to get to the top 10 in the feature race, which I mean, that's an achievement in itself, if we think about it, from brand new to F2, who has driven Indycar their entire life, essentially.

25:50.265 --> 25:59.752
I think for him, this is basically getting the experience on the F1 tracks, and it's kind of at a lower stage, and it's getting used to racing in the European circuit again.

25:59.792 --> 26:03.594
Okay, it's actually not in Europe, but it is a primarily European-based series.

26:04.015 --> 26:18.665
I’m just gonna say, it's very different to Indycar, just getting him used to it, and also maybe getting some, you know, super license points along the way, and he is, you know, it's not like it's a complete disaster, as he said, top 10 in the feature race, he's getting some points.

26:19.267 --> 26:25.691
Yeah, I think the main thing with Colton Herta is, especially this year, this is just gonna be a practice year for him.

26:26.212 --> 26:29.794
Make sure that, yeah, he gets everything down pat.

26:29.814 --> 26:41.502
Like, I think going into it, going into the year, his main thing was trying to understand how the tires worked and trying to make sure that that's something he knew how to do before he even, like, thought about getting into F1, which was very smart of him.

26:42.063 --> 26:46.446
But, yeah, the important thing is that he understood the tires and the tracks this year.

26:46.766 --> 26:51.929
But next year, I reckon that's when he's going to really start trying to get into, you know, the title race for F2.

26:52.529 --> 26:53.690
Because I'm pretty sure...

26:54.190 --> 27:02.855
I can't remember if this is correct or not, but I'm pretty sure that it's...Bottas and Perez both have, like, two-year deals or multi-year deals.

27:03.695 --> 27:07.477
So that's a good chance what Cadillac and Colton are targeting.

27:08.123 --> 27:10.504
And given how Cadillac are doing at the moment.

27:11.024 --> 27:13.666
I don't think I'd want to join them at the moment as well.

27:13.746 --> 27:17.688
I mean, P20, how glamorous to be P20.

27:18.108 --> 27:19.849
It's better than Aston Martin.

27:20.189 --> 27:23.331
I mean, they're two cheeks of the same ***.

27:24.291 --> 27:31.075
But at least, at least the Cadillac isn't trying to kill their drivers with their- whatever death machine they have.

27:31.455 --> 27:33.416
But I mean, I don't think I want to be with either.

27:33.816 --> 27:34.376
I mean, for Herta.

27:34.416 --> 27:34.596
Yeah.

27:35.927 --> 27:38.749
But for Cadillac's sake, they want to keep the adult lineup.

27:39.129 --> 27:45.174
They want to make sure that they keep their experience in F1 lineup, so that they can actually attempt to fix this when they get their rookie in.

27:45.834 --> 27:47.215
It's a little bit unction.

27:47.255 --> 27:53.840
I mean, even in the beginning, you look at Hitech in F2, Colton Herta and Miyata, who are both mid-20s.

27:54.140 --> 27:57.843
And they're both some of the most talented people on the actual grid, and yet.

27:58.472 --> 28:01.234
But unfortunately, they don't get to always show it.

28:01.334 --> 28:02.995
I mean, Miyata has been improving.

28:03.015 --> 28:07.458
I mean, this year it finally feels like, you know, something has clicked finally.

28:07.478 --> 28:10.741
You know, he's a Super Formula and a Super GT champion.

28:10.761 --> 28:12.882
I mean, we all know how good he is.

28:13.062 --> 28:15.804
And he's finally getting regular points.

28:15.884 --> 28:20.367
I mean, a top 10 again in the feature race, not in the points in the sprint, but in the feature race.

28:20.808 --> 28:28.133
I feel like, you know, there is something I want to talk about in the feature race, which is, you know, a certain someone crashing out again.

28:28.583 --> 28:29.284
Alexander Dunne?

28:30.185 --> 28:31.178
Alexander Dunne time?

28:31.257 --> 28:32.387
We knew this was coming.

28:32.547 --> 28:33.168
Who would have thought?

28:33.787 --> 28:35.308
I mean, it has to be talked about.

28:35.368 --> 28:39.169
I mean, five of the last six feature races he has crashed.

28:39.809 --> 28:44.911
I mean, he's been fast, but he can't keep on crashing like this and throwing away points.

28:45.191 --> 28:48.192
And the way it happened to Miami was honestly so funny.

28:48.813 --> 28:53.394
Kind of half spun out, and he's on the, you know, he's on like the runoff.

28:53.935 --> 28:58.116
He goes back in, and as he's going back onto the track, he just kind of hits the barriers.

28:58.556 --> 29:00.477
Like, it's like slow motion almost.

29:01.235 --> 29:05.439
Yeah, he's fast, but sometimes he gets hit with a bit of brain failure.

29:05.479 --> 29:10.363
But, you know, I think the most important thing is the fact that he does have that innate speed.

29:11.244 --> 29:12.305
Like, where would he be without it?

29:12.934 --> 29:27.221
I mean, the last three, okay, to be fair to him, Baku and Monza last year weren't his fault, but the last three feature races, Abu Dhabi, Australia, and Miami, those have all been entirely on him, and he's just throwing great points.

29:27.681 --> 29:39.167
Yeah, I kind of see him sort of similar to how Martins sort of was, you know, like, not like in terms of like driving, but in terms of just like prospects.

29:39.687 --> 29:44.448
because they're both really quick drivers, but in the case of Martins, he just never really got that chance.

29:44.988 --> 29:47.169
And I feel like it's going to be a similar thing when it comes to Dunne.

29:47.709 --> 29:52.070
But Dunne, I mean, I think that's partly down to him, just not being able to keep out of the barriers.

29:52.650 --> 29:55.351
I mean, like last year, we were all saying, this is his age.

29:55.371 --> 30:01.872
Even in the last episode, in Australia we said, he's not, even now, he's still not sorted his innate yearn for the barrier out.

30:01.952 --> 30:03.772
It's like there's some sort of attraction there.

30:03.893 --> 30:05.193
Just can't get enough, I mean.

30:06.193 --> 30:13.919
I mean, I really hope maybe when he returns to the more regular circuits, he gets this under control because he's been fast.

30:14.639 --> 30:19.503
He could be a championship contender if he just wasn't in the barriers all the time.

30:20.003 --> 30:23.106
Yeah, he hasn't won a race since Imola last year.

30:23.126 --> 30:30.771
I mean, other than Dunne, I mean, I feel bad for Bilinski because, you know, Mechachrome got struck again.

30:30.791 --> 30:33.133
We love Formula 2 and Mecachrome.

30:33.684 --> 30:41.210
It was, it was Dino, it was his teammate Dino in Australia and now it, it got Roman in Miami.

30:41.730 --> 30:44.452
It even got Stenshorne during qualifying so that’s...

30:44.972 --> 30:50.597
I mean, if there’s somebody getting Mecachromed, it's basically a staple of F2 at this point.

30:51.257 --> 31:06.843
It's one reason why, like I like F2, but it's the reason why I don't like it as much as some other series is literally because of the Mecachrome engine and how we talked about how the drivers that are good and we know are good and should be at the front aren't.

31:07.643 --> 31:17.526
I mean, we saw what's like, you know, Tsolov getting taken out by Tasanapol Inthraphuvasak which I think really sums F2 up quite nicely.

31:17.706 --> 31:28.609
Well, and I just feel like in the feature, it's like every, oh my gosh, everyone was off because we had, well, oh my God, don't even, don't even get me started on Ollie Goethe.

31:28.809 --> 31:29.509
I literally,

31:30.307 --> 31:31.267
Crashed out so hard.

31:31.367 --> 31:32.206
Anyway- so did he.

31:33.286 --> 31:39.622
Um, but we had, he had a disaster class in the sprint race.

31:39.771 --> 31:45.833
He was P3 and he had a horrible start and just like kept dropping.

31:45.893 --> 31:47.133
It was, it was a disaster.

31:47.193 --> 31:48.814
That was so bad.

31:49.234 --> 31:57.097
And then in the feature race, he, um, mostly cause it was cause of the rain, really the fact that they, the fact that they,

31:57.798 --> 32:00.261
had a standing start.

32:00.542 --> 32:01.363
What were they thinking?

32:02.384 --> 32:06.750
Anyways, so he spun out, but where he like got it, he was in the wall.

32:07.111 --> 32:11.717
But we had it because in the sprint race, how many people were out?

32:11.737 --> 32:12.058
Let's see.

32:12.444 --> 32:13.785
I think it was only three to four people.

32:13.805 --> 32:16.207
It was not as bad as the feature race.

32:16.627 --> 32:20.250
The sprint race was... Yeah, I was surprised that they did a standing start.

32:20.310 --> 32:21.711
The spray was really bad.

32:21.751 --> 32:24.713
I mean, I thought they may red flag it or something.

32:24.733 --> 32:29.236
I mean, it was really tough condition as the drivers had quite a-.

32:29.557 --> 32:34.180
I was kind of questioning why they were racing in this almost because you could barely see anything.

32:34.720 --> 32:36.762
Like, behind the safety car, you could not see.

32:37.732 --> 32:44.136
And then, uh, was it, oh my goodness, who was it that went out on slicks for like a lap?

32:44.356 --> 32:46.598
And then it was, was it Van Hoepen?

32:47.158 --> 32:50.660
It was John Bennett who went out on slicks for like a lap.

32:50.840 --> 32:54.823
Cause John Bennett was like P3 at one point.

32:55.083 --> 32:56.524
I was like, what, what is this?

32:56.564 --> 32:57.244
What's going on?

32:57.765 --> 33:03.688
Uh, but yeah, he goes out on slicks and I'm like, okay, thank you for being the guinea pig and testing them out.

33:03.748 --> 33:06.290
But dude, it was so bad that you could tell immediately that it wasn’t going to work

33:06.650 --> 33:09.192
Didn't he spin out on that lap on slicks?

33:09.232 --> 33:12.534
Yeah, it was like yellow flag conditions or something like that as well.

33:20.116 --> 33:23.217
Also, speaking of spinning out, can we talk about Cian Shields?

33:24.098 --> 33:26.179
We can always talk about Cian Shields.

33:30.321 --> 33:35.983
He spun, was it at turn 8? Did another lap, and then spun at turn 8 again.

33:36.404 --> 33:39.545
And we couldn't even tell if they were separate spins or not.

33:40.125 --> 33:42.527
I don’t even know what to say.

33:43.227 --> 33:45.068
This is why he's the goat of F2.

33:45.268 --> 33:46.548
We love Cian Shields.

33:47.349 --> 33:49.370
Put Cian Shields in F1 right now.

33:49.978 --> 33:50.698
We have to see it.

33:50.998 --> 33:53.559
Cian Shields Aston Martin 2027.

33:53.859 --> 33:54.439
I see the vision.

33:54.519 --> 33:56.279
Nando Retires, Cian Shields in.

33:57.059 --> 33:58.119
Better results than Stroll.

33:58.840 --> 34:01.260
Cian Shields F1 World Champion 2027.

34:01.300 --> 34:09.561
Yeah, I'm looking at his Wikipedia page right now and looking at the Formula 3 and Formula 2 sections.

34:09.641 --> 34:13.082
I'm seeing exclusively blue and purple right now.

34:13.442 --> 34:16.303
Best result of P11 in Imola last year.

34:16.703 --> 34:18.823
And that's including his time in F3 as well.

34:19.083 --> 34:21.323
He's just an amazing driver, guys.

34:21.803 --> 34:24.104
He's just, he's, um, sandbagging.

34:24.504 --> 34:27.144
He's been sandbagging for the past, like, I don't know, three years.

34:27.264 --> 34:28.045
Obviously.

34:28.365 --> 34:29.845
Just to give other people a chance.

34:30.425 --> 34:37.066
And as well as that, like, if you look at, if you look at Cian Shield's F2 section, he does have one race that's not blue or purple.

34:37.826 --> 34:42.887
And that's, uh, the Melbourne feature race, which was, uh, which is now in white because it was canceled.

34:43.247 --> 34:48.048
But, you know, honestly, probably one of his better results if we're talking realistically.

34:48.467 --> 34:55.292
He was sandbagging his whole career so that when he makes it to F1, he surprises everyone by just cooking everyone.

34:55.752 --> 34:56.693
That's his strategy.

34:56.993 --> 34:58.514
Well, he's doing good so far.

34:59.134 --> 35:00.615
Looking promising for him, I think.

35:01.276 --> 35:06.319
And then in the feature race, we have, was it the feature race?

35:06.519 --> 35:15.885
With the, with Maini and Camara not going through the pit lane all when they're supposed to.

35:15.905 --> 35:17.046
I thought,

35:18.770 --> 35:21.171
I really thought that they were going to get penalties for that.

35:21.651 --> 35:31.414
And they only got warnings and I'm honestly shocked that they only got let off with warnings, but I don't know.

35:32.014 --> 35:33.475
I feel like there should have been more with that.

35:34.055 --> 35:36.077
Yeah, I think that was just unfortunate.

35:36.097 --> 35:38.418
I think this timing came out too late.

35:39.219 --> 35:43.382
I mean, the marshall should be doing more than, you know, have signs clearly saying, go into pitlane.

35:43.502 --> 35:49.166
But, I mean, normally, I feel, I don't know, that is dangerous going on, especially in those conditions.

35:49.826 --> 35:56.491
I think it's just, there was some communication error, maybe that's why they weren't penalised, but still, it's a safety issue.

35:56.511 --> 35:58.913
I mean, normally, they should take a really hard line on safety.

35:59.794 --> 36:00.794
I'm not sure, because...

36:02.095 --> 36:07.082
Typically, if there's an error that isn't the driver's fault, they do still penalize that.

36:07.102 --> 36:15.994
We see that in like, if someone fails to take a 10 second penalty, because someone touched the car accidentally, they still send them back in.

36:16.775 --> 36:18.538
So, I'm not too sure.

36:19.264 --> 36:26.935
And everybody else was, and I mean, they still, I mean,  Camara finished in what, second? and Maini in fifth, it's not like they were.

36:27.555 --> 36:31.401
It impacted the podium place, but it still, it impacted the podium places.

36:32.102 --> 36:36.608
Yeah, well, and I think, I think I, I think I would have been more mad.

36:37.343 --> 36:48.368
If Camara because at one point like because with the fight at the end of the feature race — peak, by the way — but as Camara was P1 and then was P2.

36:48.828 --> 36:53.510
So I think if I, if he would have finished in P1 or P2.

36:54.917 --> 36:56.719
Um, and still only got the warning.

36:56.759 --> 37:04.105
I think I would have been more upset, but, um, I guess I could live with the warning and he's P3 anyway.

37:04.146 --> 37:06.167
So it's like, okay.

37:06.528 --> 37:17.358
And another thing about the, like the final battle at the end, one thing that I haven't really thought about that is really only hitting me now is the fact that, yeah, this really was Gabriele Mini's first win in F2.

37:18.225 --> 37:33.339
Yeah well and I was scared I thought they were gonna take it away from him because or like for a second because there was um because I saw that you was summoned to the stewards and I'm like oh no can you imagine if he loses his first win

37:34.620 --> 37:38.882
Because of the penalty, but he didn't, he didn't get, I think it was no further action.

37:39.302 --> 37:41.143
So I'm really glad that nothing happened with that.

37:41.223 --> 37:43.004
But yeah, I, I never thought about that either.

37:43.024 --> 37:44.144
I thought, oh, so this first win.

37:44.184 --> 37:47.586
And I think to have it in Miami was really cool.

37:48.106 --> 37:49.767
Um, just like Lando Norris, I guess.

37:50.349 --> 37:51.950
Yeah, exactly.

37:52.671 --> 38:00.117
And I, obviously, as a Dino fan, I was so, so thrilled about his podium.

38:00.597 --> 38:09.244
I was kind of greedy for a little bit, and I really wanted him to get the win, but I'm so happy with P2, especially considering what happened after Australia, him getting Mechachrome’d.

38:09.744 --> 38:13.087
And even in Australia, he was right up there at the front here, I mean, he...

38:13.815 --> 38:15.556
I, yeah, I was so...

38:16.377 --> 38:19.219
He literally could have won the race in Australia

38:19.279 --> 38:21.281
If it wasn't for the stupid Mecachrome engine.

38:21.901 --> 38:26.304
So this was redemption, and I'm very, very happy with P2.

38:27.125 --> 38:33.109
I think now looking to the Championship, I don't know if anybody has anything more to say on the actual races themselves.

38:33.189 --> 38:34.590
We can look towards the standings.

38:36.011 --> 38:36.611
Uh, no, I...

38:37.252 --> 38:41.255
I'm... Like, the fact that Van Hoepen is...

38:42.212 --> 38:46.377
Oh, I guess now he's P4, but he was P3 in the driver's standings.

38:50.407 --> 38:53.830
I never could have predicted Van Hoepen that high up at the driver's settings.

38:54.090 --> 38:55.831
It's nice to see Tsolov leading it.

38:56.232 --> 39:00.756
As I said earlier, I think he's very much been the best driver across the two races.

39:00.956 --> 39:05.499
And despite him being taken out in the feature race in Miami, he's still leading.

39:06.000 --> 39:11.344
I mean, he's only really top three, I mean, only really associate-, separated by one point.

39:11.444 --> 39:13.906
But as more down to Tsolov being taken out.

39:13.926 --> 39:17.089
He'd have been bound to make a position to get some points in the feature race.

39:17.549 --> 39:20.012
And Miyata P5, I mean.

39:20.953 --> 39:22.735
Is this finally the year for him?

39:22.756 --> 39:24.057
I believe so.

39:24.077 --> 39:27.822
If there's ever a year, he's not going to spend a, what, fourth year in F2.

39:28.542 --> 39:29.824
At some point, he's going to call it quits.

39:30.204 --> 39:32.928
Four years in F2, you're getting too close to Verschoor.

39:33.368 --> 39:34.289
with four years.

39:34.890 --> 39:36.592
Yeah, the trumpets are getting louder, pal.

39:37.323 --> 39:40.665
It's just, F2 is just like so fugazi sometimes.

39:41.186 --> 39:45.328
Van Hopen, P4, does not actually feel real.

39:45.948 --> 39:56.375
And I mean, someone like Alex Dunne, if you've counted where he was, where he got, where he crashed out, he probably would have been up there, but unfortunately he loves the barriers too much.

39:57.063 --> 40:06.425
Well, and if Dino didn't get Mecachromed in Australia, he for sure would be, well, because I think now he's P8, I think.

40:06.585 --> 40:06.885
Seven.

40:07.645 --> 40:08.145
P7.

40:08.485 --> 40:15.147
If, if he, oh my God, I, I just, I'm getting so, I'm getting so upset just thinking about it.

40:15.547 --> 40:21.188
If he didn't get Mecachromed in Australia, he would probably be, I guess I can't do the math right now.

40:21.588 --> 40:23.308
Where was he running in Australia?

40:24.369 --> 40:25.729
Uh, P1, I think.

40:26.172 --> 40:32.129
Oh, well, if he was P1, then that means he would be on 46 points, which would put him 11 points clear of Tsolov.

40:32.827 --> 40:40.031
Oh my God, don't even... We need to remember Tsolov also got taken out, so... Yeah, let’s say he gets like a P8.

40:40.771 --> 40:47.314
I think Beganovic and Tsolov have been the best drivers very much in both races so far, and...

40:48.094 --> 40:58.560
I mean, our next round, Canada is always going to be interesting, because once again: brand new showcase, which is always fun to see, and I reckon, and I think Tsolov is going to continue to impress.

40:59.260 --> 41:01.441
He's been really fun to watch.

41:01.911 --> 41:04.635
There's no reason to say he wouldn't.

41:04.675 --> 41:07.338
There's no evidence to suggest he's going to get slower any time now.

41:07.436 --> 41:17.677
And you know, maybe Beganovic will be up there as well, I think Herta is going to do well as well. I think things are beginning to come together for him, I think he’s gonna do well.

41:18.232 --> 41:19.973
Yeah, I'm hoping that Beganovic is up there.

41:20.413 --> 41:24.654
I'm honestly surprised Invicta isn't cooking as much.

41:24.954 --> 41:27.695
They're not cooking as much as I thought they would be.

41:28.215 --> 41:28.795
Obviously.

41:28.815 --> 41:29.476
Don’t jinx it

41:30.016 --> 41:30.296
I know.

41:30.376 --> 41:31.976
I don't want to jinx anything.

41:32.256 --> 41:33.517
I'm hoping it stays this way.

41:33.937 --> 41:43.740
But Invicta is surprisingly not as... Obviously they're still doing pretty well, but not as much as I thought they would be.

41:43.980 --> 41:45.823
They're not as dominant as they have been.

41:46.343 --> 41:47.285
Thank you.

41:47.445 --> 41:48.626
Thank you, Nikola Tsolov.

41:48.767 --> 42:00.683
Although I will say it is a bit surprising that Duerksen has managed to score in all races so far, him and Mini, I mean, Maini–the Italian one.

42:01.466 --> 42:06.988
For me, I hope, I really hope Alex Dunne can like, you know, stop kissing the barriers.

42:07.329 --> 42:11.791
I think both Alexes, Alex Dunne and Alex Powell need to learn to behave themselves.

42:12.291 --> 42:16.673
I said this about Powell earlier, but Dunne as well, please stop kissing the barriers.

42:17.093 --> 42:21.895
I think Alex Ninovic needs to share some of his good luck with Powell and Dunne.

42:22.195 --> 42:24.557
Well, no, because he got penalized from two podiums.

42:24.597 --> 42:25.758
He needs to behave too.

42:26.298 --> 42:30.441
Sure, but Ninovic has way better luck compared to the other two.

42:30.801 --> 42:33.323
I think it's just the Alex curse, they’re all cursed.

42:33.864 --> 42:36.365
Every single Alex out there needs to learn to behave.

42:37.226 --> 42:40.949
Do not name your kid Alex if you plan on putting them in motorsport.

42:41.089 --> 42:42.670
Do not name your kid Alex.

42:43.571 --> 42:49.075
We need to prevent our fellow host Alex from ever getting into a race car, I think.

42:50.824 --> 43:01.632
I think I propose an Alex race where they get all of the Alex's in motorsport, and they put them in the same car and just let them go, go ham.

43:02.133 --> 43:04.014
Alex Powell domination, trust.

43:04.294 --> 43:05.535
Yeah, that or Palou?

43:05.835 --> 43:08.437
I want to see all the Alex's in one race.

43:09.018 --> 43:12.320
And then they have a therapy session afterwards, because I think they all need it.

43:12.700 --> 43:16.363
I don't know, Alex Palou's doing pretty well for himself, I'd say.

43:16.803 --> 43:17.944
But that's just my theory, you know?

43:18.184 --> 43:19.866
Yeah, he's taking all the Alex luck.

43:20.393 --> 43:22.414
He has, even from Rossi.

43:23.014 --> 43:28.157
But yeah, so Alex Dunne needs to lock in a bit, stop kissing the barriers.

43:29.338 --> 43:33.780
And if he does do that, then hopefully he'll be higher up.

43:34.500 --> 43:38.902
I want a podium next, like in Montreal, which is in, what, three weeks?

43:39.183 --> 43:39.443
Is it?

43:40.123 --> 43:40.363
Yeah.

43:40.783 --> 43:41.024
Yeah.

43:41.064 --> 43:43.825
So I want a podium at least, if not a race win.

43:44.485 --> 43:47.327
You're asking quite a bit, man with the best finish of P6.

43:48.217 --> 43:50.698
Okay, but like he won races last season, okay?

43:51.419 --> 43:51.939
He can do it.

43:52.379 --> 43:54.280
He needs to stop kissing walls.

43:54.801 --> 43:55.901
I feel that's all he can do.

43:56.442 --> 43:57.822
Victor Martins is no longer on the grid.

43:57.842 --> 43:59.503
The only thing he has now is the walls.

43:59.764 --> 44:01.224
I was gonna make that joke.

44:01.244 --> 44:02.525
Too bad!

44:04.866 --> 44:06.807
Can we even keep that joke in the episode?

44:06.827 --> 44:08.288
Yeah, I'm keeping that in.

44:10.450 --> 44:11.310
It's fine, don't worry about it.

44:12.112 --> 44:16.476
No, but with Martins, I reckon Alex Dunne crashed into him.

44:16.977 --> 44:21.862
And then as a result, it sort of like transferred the bad luck out of Martins and into Dunne.

44:22.422 --> 44:27.427
And now Dunne is gonna live through the rest of Martins' F2 career, I guess.

44:28.988 --> 44:30.750
Just being quick with bad luck.

44:31.983 --> 44:36.146
I think Alex is one big social experiment.

44:36.186 --> 44:47.434
Everyone talks about the Mercedes Cloning Factory, but I think the real story here is whatever is going on with Alex.

44:47.494 --> 44:49.776
I think it's just one big social experiment.

44:50.296 --> 44:51.958
The Alex Cloning Factory.

44:52.798 --> 44:55.220
It's one big social experiment.

44:56.101 --> 44:56.521
I believe it.

44:57.772 --> 45:01.353
So that's it for today's episode of the Grand Prixquel podcast.

45:01.453 --> 45:02.833
Hope you guys enjoyed listening.

45:02.893 --> 45:09.914
If you have any comments, any further predictions for the rest of the seasons for both F2 and Eurocup 3, feel free to let us know.

45:10.775 --> 45:16.176
Make sure to follow us on all our socials at @grandprixquel on TikTok, Instagram, and Twitter.

45:17.276 --> 45:23.097
Next episode will be a review of the upcoming Italian F4 and British F4 weekends.

45:23.917 --> 45:25.798
So make sure to tune in for those.

45:26.538 --> 45:27.238
Thank you for listening.
